<h2>%%ReferenceStyle%%Journal, one source quoted in another</h2>
<hr>
<strong>WORKS CITED</strong>
<br><br>
Avoid where possible!
<br><br>
It is better to refer back to the original source yourself so you can check the accuracy of the quoted material. If the original source is unavailable, use &#8216;quoted in&#8217; (or &#8216;qtd. in&#8217; in a parenthetical citation). The original authors are named in your text, but only the source you actually read goes in the Works Cited list. For example, if material by Jones and Chan was quoted in a work that you read by Smith, you would only list Smith in your Works Cited. 
<br><br>
<strong>Format</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent">
	Author&#8217;s name. &#34;Title of Article (that you read).&#34; <em>Name of Journal</em>,	volume, issue, year of publication, page numbers. 
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>Example</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref-hang-indent">
	<span class="hover" title="Author&#8217;s name">Smith, Albaraa</span>. 
	&#34;<span class="hover" title="Title of Article (that you read)">High Speed Compression for Music Downloads</span>.&#34; 
	<em><span class="hover" title="Name of Journal">Journal of Internet Engineering</span></em>,
	<span class="hover" title="volume">vol. 10</span>, <span class="hover" title="issue">no. 2</span>,
	<span class="hover" title="year of publication">2056</span>, 
	<span class="hover" title="page numbers">pp. 154&#45;165</span>.
</blockquote>
<br>
